(373, 1, '2017-06-06 13:08:00', '2017-06-06 13:08:00', '<strong>Everest Two High Passes </strong><strong>Trekking</strong> is undoubtedly one of the most popular and adventurous trek comparatively to other normal trekking routes in the Everest region. You will cross over <strong>Renjo La Pass (5,369 m)</strong> and explore the beautiful Gokyo valley and Gokyo Lake in the upper Khumbu valley. From the top of <strong>Gokyo RI (5,369 m)</strong> you will enjoy more distinct and closer view of the world\'s highest peak, Mt. Everest (8,848 m), Mt. Lhotse (8,516 m), the 6th highest peak, Mt. Cho Oyu (8,201 m), Mt. Makalu (8,463 m) Mt. Ama Dablam (6,812 m) and many other snow-clad peaks of Everest region.\r\n\r\n<strong>Renjo La Pass - Gokyo Lake - Cho La Pass – Everest Base Camp Trekking</strong> after Gokyo Lake you will continue a long day trekking and cross over the <strong>Cho La Pass (5,420 m) </strong>and it takes about 9 hrs. Now you ascend slightly along the valley towards Cho La Pass. The Pass you can pass through is covered with rocks. While crossing the <strong>Cho La Pass </strong>is most of the time covered with blue Ice giving you a chill feeling. Here you can also, enjoy the stunning Panorama views of Lobuche Peak (6,119 m), Mt. Ama Dablam (6,812 m), Cholatse Peak (6,335 m) From Thagnag way crossing the<strong> Cho La Pass (5,420 m)</strong> the trail descends steeply down for an hour and then slightly descends all the way to Dzongla.\r\n\r\n<strong>Renjo La Pass - Gokyo Lake - Cho La Pass - Everest Trekking</strong> we follow the route Namche Bazaar- Thame Lungden, cross <strong>Renjo La Pass (5,369 m),</strong> Gokyo Lake, Thagnag,<strong> Cho La Pass (5,420 m),</strong> Dzongla, Lobuche, Gorakshep, <strong>Everest Base Camp (5,364 m)</strong>, <strong>Kala Pattar (5,545 m),</strong> Dingboche, Tengboche, Namche Bazaar, Lukla and fly back to Kathmandu. While heading for Renjo La Pass and Gokyo valley you will spend one extra day at Namche Bazaar for acclimatization excursion around Khumjung village.\r\n\r\n<strong>Renjo La Pass - Gokyo Lake - Cho La Pass - Everest Trekking </strong>On the same day you will enjoy excursion around Sherpa’s villages, museum and many Buddhist Monastery and Stupas in Phakdingma, Namche Bazaar, Thame, Dingbocchce, Pangboche, Tengboche and Khumjung Buddhist monasteries Khumbu valley, and immerse in the beautiful sights of Himalayan Mountain range. At Khumjung village you will encounter the local people and experience their culture and tradition. Lots of renowned climbers of Nepal belong to Sherpa’s community from upper every Himalaya Valley. Visiting Khumjung Thame and Tengboche Monasteries makes your excursion more worthwhile.\r\n\r\n<strong>Everest Two High Passes </strong><strong>Trekking</strong> at the same time you will visit Tengboche where a famous Sherpa’s Buddhist Monastery is located. In Thame and Tengboche monasteries you will meet Buddhist monks and see their daily rituals. This is long trek with many cultural and natural highlights and recommendable only to those trekkers who are keen to walk at higher altitude for longer days.', 'Everest Two High Passes Trekking', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '52-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-06 13:08:00', '2017-06-06 13:08:00', '', 52, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/52-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(376, 1, '2017-06-11 07:56:36', '2017-06-11 07:56:36', '<strong>What is</strong> <strong>Camping Trekking? </strong>\r\n\r\nThere are no lodges or hotels available in some remote and Nepal government controlled areas especially in Manang, Langtang, Makalu , Rolwaling, Ganesh Himal, Bhairav Kunda,  Dhaulagiri, Upper and Lower Dolpo and many other areas. Trekking to these areas is quite difficult due to non-availability of lodges, enough food and out of easy access by means of transport. So, full board camping is the only option for trekking to all these above areas. <strong>High Mountain Himalaya Treks &amp; Expeditions </strong>provide  all necessary camping equipments that include high quality kitchen equipments, sleeping tents, dinning tents, toilet tent, shower tent, dining table, chairs, mattresses, staff\'s tents, food, fuel and of course, sleeping bags are provided.\r\n\r\nThe trekking guide leads the whole crew. Our porters carry the loads, Sherpas set up tents and well- trained cook and kitchen helpers prepare the delicious meals (breakfast, lunch &amp; dinner) every day. All the remote areas are physically demanding as it requires 7-8 hours daily hike, cross over several mountain passes and walk through places untouched by mass tourism. Trekkers set their own pace carrying their small backpack with a water bottle, a camera and necessary clothing stuff through sleepy countryside experiencing local culture and traditional lifestyle of the people. Our guide will brief you about the local culture and customs of the areas you trek through.\r\n\r\nCamping trekking in Nepal offers a mind-blowing experience while exploring unique landscape with a diverse range of pristine eco-systems. You trek through isolated valleys and high Mountain passes, jungle with flora and fauna, cascades and lakes. Dolpo in northwest region of  Nepal (maximum elevation 4,500m) attracts trekkers with its Phoksundo Lake and unparalleled scenery.\r\n\r\nAs compared to teahouse trekking, the cost of full board camping is normally expensive especially for smaller groups. Trekkers who travel in any of remote and government restricted/ controlled areas in Nepal must book the camping trekking through government-registered trekking agency like <strong>High Mountain Himalaya Treks &amp; Expeditions</strong> for issuing permits, guide arrangements under the supervision of Government Immigration office of Nepal. Camping treks offer an extra thrill of trekking in the Nepal Himalayas.', 'Nepal Camping Trekking', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'nepal-camping-trekking', '', '', '2017-06-11 08:42:18', '2017-06-11 08:42:18', '', 18, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/?page_id=376', 0, 'page', '', 0),
