(469, 1, '2017-06-11 10:06:53', '2017-06-11 10:06:53', '<strong>Upper Mustang Trekking </strong>the arid and isolated Upper Mustang lies in the north-west region of Nepal. Trekking to Upper Mustang inspire any travelers to explore centuries-old monasteries, Stupas (Chortens), Mani wall, barley fields created through the painstaking lab our of local people, the high altitude trails and extreme deserts, religion, culture and life style of the local people.\n\n<strong>Upper Mustang-Lo Manthang Trekking</strong> gives you the opportunity to go where only few have been before. During the trek you will walk through arid, high deserts and sparse villages inhabited mostly by people of Tibetan origin. There you will see the men folk are either traders or farmers while the women mostly tend the fields. The views en route up are wonderful with the peaks north into Nepal and Tibet.  <strong>Trekking to Upper Mustang-Lo Manthang </strong>En route, you will see many different small flowers and also many nests of Himalayan Griffins high up in the cliff-faces, noticeable from their white below them (vulture droppings), and will see these majestic birds with their three meter wing-spans circling high above us. After walking about two hours from Samar you will reach Chungsi caves, one of the ubiquitous Guru Rimpoche\'s (Guru Padma Sambhava) meditation caves. Now, you will find a red painted Monastery at the Chungsi Caves which look as if it\'s stuck on to the vertical wall. In addition, you will also visit Rangjung Chortens, (Natural Bud Stupas) one of the most sacred places in Upper Mustang.The name Chortens means self-formation. Because inside there are two large stalagmites in a Chortens (Stupas) like formation. Two famous Buddhist saints, Guru Rinpoche\'s (Guru Padma Sambhava) and Atisha stayed in this caves centuries ago. There are many prayer flags and Khathas on the ceiling and pilgrims have left small clay figures inside where you can see natural holy spring water blessed by Guru Rimpoche\'s (Guru Padma Sambhava).\n\n<strong>Upper Mustang-Lo Manthang Trekking </strong>when you spend two extra days one day in <strong>Tsarang (3,560 m)</strong> Rest and acclimatization day at Tsaring; we will have a pilgrimage of the monasteries and Stupas (Chortens), the monastery which is the second oldest one in the world where we will see holy scriptures; Kangyur and Tengyur (100 volumes original teaching of the Syakya Muni Buddha and 225 volumes commentaries written in pure gold by the masters of the Nalanda university about the buddha\'s original teaching) and we also will learn about life style of the Tibetan Buddhist monks.\n\nAnd one extra day in <strong>Lo-Manthang (3,840 m)</strong> this day will be spent in this mystical and isolated town. You will awake to the mystical sounds of monks chanting and the heady sent of temple candles. After having breakfast you will visit the four major temples within the city walls. The major attraction of this area is the three storey’s Jampa Lhakhang, the red Thubchen Gompa with a massive assembly hall, Chodey Gompa and Choprang Gompa. After visiting the Monasteries and Stupas (Chortens) you will take a walk to visit the ACAP office.\n\n<strong>Upper Mustang Trekking </strong>then, you will go for day trip to Tsoshar village, also known as the, “Cave Village’’. You will set off on horse or by Jeep (accompanied by horseman, no horse riding skill is required) and head to Tsoshar village, lies on the grassy plains with sandy cliffs. It takes about two hours. The trail descends from Lo Manthang, after crossing the river; it is straight to Tsoshar village. You will have excellent view of Mt. Nilgiri and Tilicho peaks towering before your eyes and panorama view of Lo Manthang in the backdrop along the trail.\n\nOn the rocky hillside, lie the Nyiphuk Gompa of Nyingma sect and Garphuk Gompa of Ngor sect, two monasteries of the Tsoshar village. During the excursion out of Lo-Manthang you will visit the wonderful five stories man made Caves having hundreds of chambers, believed to have once used as meditation rooms by monks and shelters by ancient guards to protect the Kingdom full day you will enjoys there. Ladders are placed to climb from one floor to another, need to be extra cautious here. Parts of the chambers are off limit to tourist. The small monasteries feature few monks with prayer rooms and it offers great view of the valley and Himalayan ranges. We follow the same trail back to Lo-Manthang in the late afternoon.\n\n<strong>Upper Mustang Trekking</strong> from Lo Manthang to Ghami this day more beater you will set off on horses we walk up through pastures studded with juniper, and have the chance to look back at Lo Manthang. Our return route is on the same side of the Kali Gandaki, because the eastern part is even less inhabited, more strenuous for walking and drinking water can be hard to find. Gradually we say goodbye to the Lo Manthang plain (sometimes known as ‘The Plain of Prayers’) and after about two hours there is no sign at all that such a gem of a city is concealed in one of those rocky valleys.\n\nIn front of us the mass of the Himalayas reappears and we negotiate the <strong>highest pass, Chgo La (4230 m). </strong>There is also a group of Stupas (Chortens) standing in front of the red wall which forms the end of the valley. Again, the architecture here is like an organic extension of nature. According to legend when the famous Buddhist master Guru Rinpoche (Guru Padma Sambhava) came to the area and fought and destroyed a demon, its intestines landed at the site where the Mani wall stands, its lungs near the red cliffs behind and its heart at the spot where not only Upper Mustang’s in the world oldest <strong>monastery, of Lo Gekar Gompa,</strong> was built.\n\nLeaving the monastery, we have a short but steep walk down the yellow canyon to Tamar, seeing fields in the southern and western part of the valley and large red vertical cliffs in the North West. After our time in such very barren landscape with little in the way of color contrasts, the combination of red rock, blue sky, green grass and white yaks and horses seems very intense! Above the village are numerous caves, but their entrances are only accessible to rock climbers. At the entrance to the canyon is an unusual looking Chortens-the top looks like a bush because of the hundreds of prayer flags woven into it.\n\nAround the Stupas (Chortens) are hundreds of erected stones. With Nilgiri visible again, we walk past more caves on our way south and then there is a gradual hill climb bringing us above Ghami, where we can see the town, the long Mani wall and the pass we climbed five days ago!\n\n<strong>Upper Mustang Trekking</strong> from Chhusang to Muktinath (3,800 m) Soon we are at Tetang’s village Mani wall and beautiful Chortens, which has two of the auspicious symbols painted on each side. After an early start we have a good view of the village of Tetang, which consists of two separate settlements surrounded by high walls and from a distance looks like a large fort. The ascent to a plateau is steep and the trail here can be rather difficult to locate. There is an easy walk over a plain, after which comes about three hours of steep walking uphill, with the narrow trail getting precipitous at times, with loose black gravel.\n\nAfter ascending high in the valley the trail makes a right turn and the Gyu La Pass (4077 m) becomes visible above. At the pass, the mountains seem amazingly close, with Thorung, although the lowest peak, looking particularly impressive, having large glaciers clinging to its steep flanks. Tilicho is covered by snow with indented glaciers, while the summit of Annapurna further back does not actually seem as high as its 8000m +. Even Nilgiri’s almost sheer north face is also covered by glaciers. It is a moderate walk down to Muktinath, with stunning views of Dhaulagiri and Annapurna. Their summits are only 34km apart, which accounts for the tremendous depth of the Kali Gandaki valley. Getting to Muktinath involves crossing another valley, which takes some time. The sporadic houses start to become more numerous as we get nearer Muktinath. Where you can see natural 108 holy spring water blessed by Guru Rimpoche\'s (Guru Padma Sambhava), which have their source in or around Muktinath and bathing here is believed to bring good luck. Many people also collect the spring water in bottles to take home to relatives. Also at Muktinath is the legendary flame coming out of a rock, around which a Buddhist Monasteries, Stupas (Chortens) and Mani wall has been created.\n\nThe trek to this land of magic and mystery begins at <strong>Jomsom</strong>, following a <strong>flight to Jomsom</strong> and <strong>trek to Kagbeni</strong>, a ruined citadel town that guards the entrance into <strong>Mustang</strong>. Entering Mustang, we visit the more then 16th century monasteries at <strong>Lo Gekar Gompa </strong><strong>(3920 m), Tsarang Gompa (3,560 m)</strong> and the fortress city of <strong>Lo-Manthang.</strong> Here, we observe the splendor and traditions of more than old Tibet. On our return journey from Upper Mustang we may visit the sacred pilgrimage site of <strong>Muktinath (3,800 m) </strong>and end our trek in Jomsom Bazar (2,710 m).', 'Upper Mustang-Lo Manthang Trekking', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '466-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-06-11 10:06:53', '2017-06-11 10:06:53', '', 466, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/466-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
