(1017, 1, '2019-01-01 17:08:45', '2019-01-01 17:08:45', '<strong>Cultural Trekking to Annapurna Region.......!</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is a short and easy trek in to the <strong>Annapurna region</strong> designed for trekkers with a limited time schedule. <strong>Cultural Trek to Annapurna Region</strong> offers some wonderful close- up views of the <strong>Himalayan mountain</strong> range. The trip starts at Phedi after 2 hours drive from Pokhara.\r\n\r\nAfter Phedi you will begin the trek through patchwork valleys, dense mossy forests and past waterfalls where you can stop to cool yourself. Around every corner you will be tempted by a tantalizing glimpse of the high mountains, whole horizons will be revealed to you as you slowly ascend the higher elevations. During the hill walk, you pass through different Gurung, Magar and Brahmin villages where you get an insight into their diverse cultural and social practices. In a short period, you can experience their colorful culture of the local people and find how Buddhist and Hindu people are living in harmony and peace.\r\n\r\nAll the way you follow the <strong>Modi gorge valley</strong> through rhododendron and orchid forest and reach a culturally rich village called Pothana where <strong>Gurung ethnic community</strong> is inhabited in majority. During the trek you can see the panoramic views of Mt. Machapuchhre (fishtail), Annapurna South, Lamjung Himal, Hiunchuli (6441m) and Dhaulagiri more distinctly if weather permits. An excursion around the village you will have an opportunity to watch the daily activities of the villagers from milching the buffalows to their daily chores on the farms.After <strong>Pothana village</strong> you will walk further uphill to another village called <strong>Ghandruk village in Nepal</strong> where you will find the same Gurung ethnic community who are known is \'<strong>Gurkhas</strong>\'. They have a glorious history created in the <strong>Second World War</strong>. Here, you will see how the traditional houses with stone roofs have been preserved till today and during your stay in the village you can visit the local museum.', 'Cultural Trekking to Annapurna Region', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '515-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-01-01 17:08:45', '2019-01-01 17:08:45', '', 515, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/demo/515-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1018, 1, '2019-01-01 17:17:04', '2019-01-01 17:17:04', '<strong>Manaslu Circuit trekking</strong> is considered the best hike in Nepal with mesmerizing Mountain vistas of the Ganesh and Manaslu Himalayan ranges and to explore the ethnic cultures and traditional lifestyle of mountain people perhaps not found on any other trekking regions. The trekking route circumnavigates the World\'s <strong>eighth highest peak, Manaslu</strong> (8,163 m).<strong> Manaslu region</strong> is officially opened to trekkers in 1991 and getting much popular for trekking these days.\r\n\r\nIt is an absolutely stunning trek starting in the rural town of Arughat (500 m). A bumpy jeep ride on mud and rock-laden tracks from Dhadingbesi up to<strong> Arughat</strong> is a wonderful experience. The trail follows through the bank of the roaring <strong>Budi Gandaki river</strong> and passes along mid- hills and finally emerges into the high, arid desert region that is actually a part of the Tibetan Plateau where people of Tibetan origin dwell and where the predominant religion-Tibetan Buddhism (Bon Po) still exists. On the way, there are many countless beautiful waterfalls are seen, some wonderful protected Buddhist monasteries, soaring white peaks and glaciers, and beautiful rhododendrons in full bloom (especially in the spring season).\r\n\r\n<strong>Manaslu Circuit trek</strong> is challenging while crossing of the Larkya La Pass which requires excellent physical stamina. There are many ascents and decents along the trail up to the base camp of Mt. Manaslu. <strong>Crossing Larkya La pass</strong> (5106m) is truly challenging and ecstasy that you gain out of panoramic mountain vista including Manaslu, Himlung and other peaks is unforgettable and lifetime experience. In <strong>Sama village</strong> you take an extra day to acclimatise and explore Sama gaon monastery, or if you are really energetic you may hike to the base camp of the 8th highest mountain and a beautiful glacier lake.\r\n\r\nBeing a government controlled area; Manaslu region needs a <strong>special trekking permit</strong> to organize trekking. Only limited numbers of tourists are allowed to visit this region every year. To complete the Manaslu circuit trekking, one should be fit to properly acclimatize with higher altitude and to <strong>cross high passes.</strong>', 'Manaslu Circuit trekking', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '474-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-01-01 17:17:04', '2019-01-01 17:17:04', '', 474, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/demo/474-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1019, 1, '2019-01-01 17:21:26', '2019-01-01 17:21:26', 'For those looking for the cutting edge of adventure trek through the rugged and non-touristic area in Nepal, <strong>Jumla - Rara trekking</strong> will be the best option!\n\n<strong>Jumla &amp; Rara</strong> lie in the remote <strong>Karnali region</strong> of mid-western Nepal. Jumla is a Trans -Himalayan valley with high ridges covered with coniferous forests &amp; alpine pastures. <strong>Rara Lake</strong>, the largest lake in Nepal and <strong>Rara National Park,</strong> the country\'s smallest national park with the area of 106 sq. km enhance the attraction to trekkers to this region. The park’s elevation ranges from 2,800m to 4,039m. This beautiful high altitude <strong>Rara Lake</strong> is surrounded by alpine meadows and forests of blue pine, black juniper, Himalayan cypress and spruce, whilst in the background the magnificent view of snow-capped peaks of the Himalayas is fantastic. Snow trout is the only fish species so far recorded in the lake. A small part of the park serves as an ideal habitat for the endangered musk deer. Other animals found in the park include Himalayan black bear, leopard, goral, Himalayan tahr and wild boar. Resident Gallinaceous birds and migrant waterfowls are found around the lake. The great-crested grebe, black-necked grebe and red-crested pochard are seen during the winter. Other common birds are the snow-cock, chukor partridge, Impeyan pheasant (danphe), kalij pheasant and blood\n\nThe views of Sisne, Kanjiroba Himal and tranquil surroundings enhanced by the reflection of Gurchi Lekh on the blue water of the lake of Rara make the trek a worth. Upper and Lower routes of Great Himalayan Trail (GHT)   pass through the shores of Rara Lake,\n\n<strong>Trekking to Jumla - Rara</strong> remote area in Nepal offers glimpses of in culture, picturesque villages and scenery very different from other parts of the country. Being fairly a high altitude trek above 3062m, <strong>Jumla Rara area</strong> is free from monsoon thunderstorms and one can accomplish the trek even in the monsoon which is the best time to visit. The trek is accessible by a flight to Jumla via Nepalgunj.', 'Jumla - Rara Trekking', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '773-autosave-v1', '', '', '2019-01-01 17:21:26', '2019-01-01 17:21:26', '', 773, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/demo/773-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
