(1079, 1, '2019-01-03 08:51:04', '2019-01-03 08:51:04', 'Paldor Peak (5,896m/19,339ft.) lies in a remote area of the Langtang region at the south-east end of the Ganesh Himal. This area offers excellent walking trails for climbers and trekkers alike. The trails join Tiru and Karpu ridge at the head of the MailungKhola, a tributary of the TrishuliGandaki River. This peak can be climbed either via the North East, South East, West and South West Ridge. It was first climbed by Bill Tilman, Peter Lloyd, Tenzing Sherpa and Da Namgyal in 1949 through the North-East Ridge.\r\n\r\nWhile trekking, you will catch a glimpse of stunning tranquil lakes, beautiful waterfalls, great Himalayan landscapes and lush green farming terraces. You also get an insight into the lifestyle and culture of the local indigenous communities. The quickest way to begin Paldor peak climbing is by 7 hours’ drive from Kathmandu to Sabrubensi in the Langtang region. From here we begin the trek crossing the BhoteKosi River way up to Tangjet and Gatlang villages, then head northwards along the ridge before descending into the forest above Mailung.\r\n\r\nThe moraine filled valley below Paldor peak is accessed from here. After climbing Paldor peak, we trek downhill to Sybrubensi in 4 or 5 days and take a land transport to Kathmandu. High Mountain Himalaya Treks and Expedition has designed Paldor Peak Climbing for 17 days itinerary but it can be customized as per trekkers’ interest and time schedule.', 'Paldor Peak Climbing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '831-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-01-03 08:51:04', '2019-01-03 08:51:04', '', 831, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/demo/831-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1080, 1, '2019-01-03 08:52:28', '2019-01-03 08:52:28', '<strong>Naya Kanga peak</strong> (5844m.), rises to the west of Ganja La Pass and the  south of Kyanjin Gompa (3,749m/12,297ft) is a popular but difficult peak to climb.It is located north from Kathmandu in the Langtang region. The normal trekking route that we follow to <strong>climb Naya Kanga peak</strong> is either Syabrubensi or Helambu region. The reward for climbing Naya Kanga is viewing of the spectacular mountains such as Langtang Lerung, (8,046m/27,749ft) Langshisa Ri (6,370m/20,894ft), Ganesh Himal, Pemthang Ri (6,836m/22,422ft), Pemthang Kapro Ri (6,830m/22,402ft) etc. The normal route of <strong>ascent to Naya Kanga</strong> is via the North - East Ridge over a line on ice and snow.Much of the climb is straightforward, but there is one fairly steep section where belaying is necessary.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe best way you can do is to <strong>cross over Ganjala pass</strong> (5130.m), the tricky but direct pass between Langtang and Helambu region. The climb to <strong>Naya Kanga</strong> is often combined with a crossing of the Ganjala pass and set up two camps .As there is no teahouse is available between <strong>Kyanjin Gompa</strong> and Ganjala pass we need to be well - equipped with camping gear, food and utensils and camping crew. The first camp is at Ganja La base camp some 500 meters above Kyanjin Gompa and the second camp is  a high camp at around 4,900 meters. The summit offers sublime views of the peaks lying along the<strong> Langtang Valley </strong>and into Tibet.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe route is approached on the trail across the Ganja La, the tricky but direct pass from Langtang to Helambu. The climb is often incorporated into a crossing of the pass and can be done with two camps. The first is <strong>Ganja La base camp</strong> some 500 meters above Kyanjin Gompa and the second a high camp at around 4,900 meters. The summit offers sublime views of the peaks lying along the Langtang Valley and into Tibet.', 'Naya Kanga (Ganjala Chuli)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '833-autosave-v1', '', '', '2019-01-03 08:52:28', '2019-01-03 08:52:28', '', 833, 'http://highhimalayatreks.com/demo/833-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
